---
import ToolPage from '../../layouts/ToolPage.astro'
import JsonToTypescriptIsland from '../../islands/JsonToTypescriptIsland'
import { getToolMeta } from '@devkits/core'

const meta = getToolMeta('json-to-typescript')!
---

<ToolPage meta={meta}>
  <JsonToTypescriptIsland client:load />

  <section class="mt-12 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-4">How to Use</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>
        Paste a JSON object or array into the left panel. The tool instantly generates TypeScript
        type definitions in the right panel. Use the options to choose between <code>interface</code>
        and <code>type</code> syntax, set the root type name, and control whether optional
        properties are inferred from nullable fields.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is particularly useful when integrating a new REST API or third-party SDK: copy the
        response body from your browser's Network tab, paste it here, and immediately get typed
        interfaces to use in your TypeScript project. It also works for configuration files,
        database query results, and any other JSON-shaped data you need to type-check.
      </p>
      <p>
        Nested objects are converted to nested interfaces, arrays are typed as <code>T[]</code>,
        and <code>null</code> values produce union types with <code>null</code>. All conversion
        runs client-side.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Does JSON to TypeScript handle deeply nested objects and arrays?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Yes. The converter recursively processes nested objects, generating a separate named
          interface for each level. Arrays of objects produce a typed array whose element type is
          inferred from the first item in the array. Arrays of primitives produce
          <code>string[]</code>, <code>number[]</code>, etc.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Should I use interface or type for API response shapes?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Both work. <code>interface</code> is preferred for object shapes that may be extended
          elsewhere in your codebase, because it supports declaration merging. <code>type</code>
          is more flexible — it can express unions, intersections, and mapped types that
          <code>interface</code> cannot. For plain data models, either choice is fine and largely
          a matter of team convention.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">How are null and undefined handled in the generated types?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Fields whose value is <code>null</code> in the sample JSON are typed as
          <code>T | null</code>, where <code>T</code> is inferred from other array items or
          treated as <code>unknown</code> when no additional information is available. Missing
          keys compared to sibling objects are marked as optional with <code>?</code>.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Can I convert the output directly into a .ts file?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Yes — copy the generated code and paste it into any <code>.ts</code> or
          <code>.d.ts</code> file in your project. The output is valid TypeScript with no
          additional imports required.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ToolPage>
